# HQ theming (light / dark)

Alliance HQ chrome must stay theme-safe. Prefer reusable tokens and components over one-off styles.

## Source of truth

Semantic colors live in [`src/app/globals.css`](src/app/globals.css):

- `:root` — light values
- `:root.dark` — dark values
- `@theme inline` — Tailwind `hq-*` color names (`bg-hq-canvas`, `text-hq-fg`, `border-hq-warning`, …)

Always use Tailwind `hq-*` utilities (or `var(--hq-…)` in CSS). Do **not** assume dark mode is the default.

## Prefer tokens over hardcoded hex

| Do | Don't |
| --- | --- |
| `border-hq-warning/40 bg-hq-warning/10 text-hq-warning` | `border-[#d29922] bg-[#d2992210] text-[#e3b341]` |
| `text-hq-danger` / `border-hq-danger` | `text-[#f85149]` for errors |
| `bg-hq-surface border-hq-border text-hq-fg` | One-off canvas/surface hex |

If no token fits, **add a semantic CSS variable** to both `:root` and `:root.dark`, wire it in `@theme`, then use the new `hq-*` class in the same change. Do not ship a UI-only hex that only looks right in one theme.

## Semantic roles

Use tokens by meaning:

- Surfaces: `hq-canvas`, `hq-surface`, `hq-surface-muted`, `hq-border`
- Text: `hq-fg`, `hq-fg-muted`, `hq-fg-subtle`
- Actions / links: `hq-accent`, `hq-selected` / `hq-selected-fg`
- Status: `hq-warning` (caution banners), `hq-danger` (errors), `hq-success` / `hq-green` (success)
- Brand: `hq-discord` (already tokenized)

Prefer opacity modifiers on tokens (`/10`, `/40`, `/50`) over unique hex+alpha literals.

## Reuse before invent

1. Match an existing notice/banner pattern already in the app (e.g. warning: `border-hq-warning/40 bg-hq-warning/10 text-hq-warning`).
2. If the same chrome appears in two or more places, extract a small shared component or shared class string — do not copy-paste divergent one-offs.
3. Prefer existing shared UI primitives over new ad-hoc layout chrome when they fit.

## Domain-colored components (mechanism / brand palettes)

Some components use **Tailwind color-scale classes** where the hue carries domain meaning — cyan for Price Is Freight, blue for VS, purple for R4, emerald for R3, amber for donations, etc. These **cannot** be replaced with generic `hq-*` tokens because the color itself communicates a game mechanic.

**Every such class must have a `dark:` counterpart.** Without one, the color is only readable in whatever theme the author happened to be using.

### Dual-mode pattern

| Layer | Light mode | Dark mode |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Background | Solid pastel (`bg-blue-100`) | Translucent tint (`dark:bg-blue-500/15`) |
| Text | Dark hue (`text-blue-700`) | Light hue (`dark:text-blue-200`) |
| Border | Mid hue (`border-blue-500`) | Same or translucent (`dark:border-blue-500`) |

Full example for a VS-themed section:

```
border-blue-500 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 dark:bg-blue-500/15 dark:text-blue-200
```

### Canonical maps

Mechanism and template cell classes live in [`src/lib/trains/mechanism-styles.ts`](src/lib/trains/mechanism-styles.ts) (`MECHANISM_STYLES`) and [`src/lib/trains/calendar-cell-styles.shared.ts`](src/lib/trains/calendar-cell-styles.shared.ts) (`TEMPLATE_CELL_STYLES`, not exported). **New entries must use the dual-mode shape above** (light pastel + `dark:` tint/text). Legacy entries may still be dark-biased (`bg-blue-500/15 text-blue-200` without light counterparts) — migrate them when you touch that surface.

### CTAs inside themed panels

Buttons and links inside domain-colored sections are the most common readability failure:

| Do | Don't |
| --- | --- |
| `bg-cyan-100 text-cyan-700 dark:bg-cyan-500/10 dark:text-cyan-100` | `bg-cyan-500/10 text-cyan-100` (invisible on white) |
| `text-cyan-600 dark:text-cyan-300` for links | `text-cyan-300` (invisible on white) |

### Fade / gradient overlays

Never hardcode a dark-mode background hex in inline `style`. Prefer `hq-*` surface tokens (they already flip with theme) over hex literals that happen to match `--hq-canvas`:

| Do | Don't |
| --- | --- |
| `bg-gradient-to-b from-hq-canvas via-hq-canvas/60 to-transparent` | `style={{ background: "linear-gradient(…, #0d1117 …)" }}` or `dark:from-[#0d1117]` |

Known legacy debt (migrate when those surfaces are next touched): `PriceIsRightTicketsPanel`, `TrainPivotBanner`, and related train panels still use bare `text-cyan-300` / hardcoded `#0d1117` gradients.

### Badge / pill accents

Small colored badges (e.g. takedown override, rank indicators) follow the same rule:

```
bg-violet-100 text-violet-700 dark:bg-violet-500/20 dark:text-violet-200
```

## Allowed exceptions

- Third-party brand colors already exposed as tokens (e.g. `hq-discord`)
- Charts / data viz with a fixed palette documented next to the series config
- Decorative assets that are not interactive chrome (and are not expected to flip with theme)

## Checklist before shipping UI

- [ ] Colors go through `hq-*` (or a new token added in light **and** dark) — domain-colored components excepted; see above
- [ ] No new arbitrary hex for borders/backgrounds/text unless an exception above applies
- [ ] Domain-colored components use dual-mode classes (light + `dark:`) — no bare `text-cyan-100` or `bg-blue-500/10` without a light-mode counterpart
- [ ] Fade/gradient overlays use `hq-*` surface tokens (e.g. `from-hq-canvas`), not hardcoded dark hex in `style` or `dark:from-[#…]`
- [ ] Warning / error / success use the matching semantic token
- [ ] Spot-check light and dark (or reason from token definitions) before merge
